        "---\n",
        "title: \"BERT vs GenAI for Complaint Detection\"\n",
        "author: \"Vyshnavi Yalamanchi\"\n",
        "date: \"2026-04-10\"\n",
        "categories: [NLP, GenAI, BERT, Python]\n",
        "description: \"Comparing a fine-tuned BERT model against LLaMA 3.3 for classifying customer complaints.\"\n",
        "image: \"../../images/bert_genai_cover.png\"\n",
        "execute:\n",
        "  echo: true\n",
        "  warning: false\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  html:\n",
        "    code-fold: true\n",
        "    code-tools: true\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Question\n",
        "\n",
        "I wanted to know: is it better to fine-tune a specialised model like **BERT**, or just use a large language model like **LLaMA 3.3** out of the box? This project compares both approaches for customer complaint severity classification^[Done as part of my MSc coursework at DCU.].\n",
        "\n",
        "## Setup"
      ],
      "id": "5b0825e8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import plotly.express as px\n",
        "import plotly.graph_objects as go"
      ],
      "id": "1baadddf",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Results\n",
        "\n",
        "Here's what I found after running both pipelines:"
      ],
      "id": "29c59f0d"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Model': ['BERT (Fine-tuned)', 'LLaMA 3.3 (Zero-shot)', 'DistilBERT', 'GPT-3.5 (Baseline)'],\n",
        "    'Accuracy': [0.92, 0.88, 0.86, 0.83],\n",
        "    'F1': [0.91, 0.87, 0.84, 0.80],\n",
        "    'Latency_ms': [45, 800, 25, 1200]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "df"
      ],
      "id": "44affbc0",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## How the Two Pipelines Work\n",
        "\n",
        "The approaches are quite different. BERT needs labelled data and training time, while LLaMA just needs a good prompt:\n",
        "\n",
        "```{mermaid}\n",
        "graph TD\n",
        "    subgraph BERT Pipeline\n",
        "        A[Raw Text] --> B[Tokenise]\n",
        "        B --> C[Fine-tune Model]\n",
        "        C --> D[Predict Label]\n",
        "    end\n",
        "    subgraph GenAI Pipeline\n",
        "        E[Raw Text] --> F[Write Prompt]\n",
        "        F --> G[Send to LLaMA API]\n",
        "        G --> H[Parse Response]\n",
        "    end\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "For evaluation, I used the F1-score, which balances precision and recall:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$F_1 = 2 \\cdot \\frac{\\text{Precision} \\times \\text{Recall}}{\\text{Precision} + \\text{Recall}}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## Accuracy vs Speed\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the trade-off that matters most in production. BERT is fast and accurate; GenAI is flexible but slow:"
      ],
      "id": "52304f02"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| fig-cap: \"Accuracy vs inference speed for each model\"\n",
        "fig = px.scatter(df, x=\"Latency_ms\", y=\"Accuracy\", color=\"Model\", size=\"F1\",\n",
        "                 labels={\"Latency_ms\": \"Latency (ms)\", \"Accuracy\": \"Accuracy\"},\n",
        "                 template=\"plotly_white\")\n",
        "fig.update_traces(marker=dict(size=20, line=dict(width=2, color='DarkSlateGrey')))\n",
        "fig.show()"
      ],
      "id": "875bc628",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Where BERT Gets It Wrong\n",
        "\n",
        "Even BERT makes mistakes. The confusion matrix shows it sometimes mislabels negative complaints as positive:"
      ],
      "id": "aa4f0ea7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| fig-cap: \"Confusion matrix for the fine-tuned BERT model\"\n",
        "z = [[150, 15], [20, 115]]\n",
        "fig = px.imshow(z, text_auto=True,\n",
        "                x=['Pred Negative', 'Pred Positive'],\n",
        "                y=['Actual Negative', 'Actual Positive'],\n",
        "                color_continuous_scale='Blues')\n",
        "fig.show()"
      ],
      "id": "7c47f5fd",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## What I Learned\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "**Bottom line:** If you have labelled data and need speed, go with BERT. If you need a quick prototype without training data, GenAI is surprisingly good — 88% accuracy with zero training.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "In practice, I think the best approach is a hybrid: use GenAI to label your data, then fine-tune BERT on those labels. You get the best of both worlds.\n",
        "\n",
